<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 6:8<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I2741d4f0630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>6.</label.designator><headtext>Judicial Notice of Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f7afe682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>6:8.</label.designator><headtext>Law—Federal</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Georgia courts take judicial notice of the “laws of the United States,” including acts of Congress.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I784ff95074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017104" w-serial-number="2015934849" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Icfdef0f274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Kramer v. Yokely</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I7850206074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Court of Appeals held that a state court could take judicial notice of an order from the federal district court in an underlying and related civil rights action in which the attorneys had represented the same client as plaintiff. <eos/><bos/>The court noted that, since the district court published its order, all parties and the state trial court had notice that the federal district court would rely upon its order. <eos/><bos/>Moreover, the reverse is also true; the district courts may take judicial notice of state court records within their geographic jurisdiction.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7850206174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>However, trial courts are not authorized to take judicial notice of federal opinions if they are unpublished decisions.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7850206274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>] Courts are, however, required to take judicial notice of matters published in the Federal Register.[<eos/><?page no="165"?><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7850206374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I784ff95074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017104" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-2-220" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Icfdd916074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-2-220</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017104" w-serial-number="1873005037" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="Icfdd916274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Morris v. Davidson, 49 Ga. 361, 1873 WL 2592 (1873)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017104" w-serial-number="1959125183" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Icfdd916674d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">City of Carrollton v. Walker, 215 Ga. 505, 111 S.E.2d 79 (1959)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Courts will take judicial notice of a treaty of the United States, and it will predominate over Georgia statutory law. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017104" w-serial-number="1981133021" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Icfde54b274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Camp v. Sellers &amp; Co., Ltd., 158 Ga. App. 646, 281 S.E.2d 621 (1981)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7850206074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017104" w-serial-number="2015934849" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Icfdf180274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Kramer v. Yokely, 291 Ga. App. 375, 662 S.E.2d 208 (2008)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7850206174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017104" w-serial-number="1990170175" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000350" ID="Icfdfb44174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Redner v. Citrus County, Florida, 919 F.2d 646 (11th Cir., 1990)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7850206274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017104" w-serial-number="2034341702" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Icfe0297274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Garner v. U.S. Bank Nat. Ass&apos;n, 329 Ga. App. 86, 763 S.E.2d 748 (2014)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7850206374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator><?page no="165"?>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017104" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-2-220" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Icfe0c5b074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-2-220</cite.query> (<begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“the laws of the United States and of the several states thereof as published by authority”<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>); <cite.query w-src-number="0287017104" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="44USCAS1507" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="Icfe0c5b174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">44 U.S.C.A. § 1507</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017104" w-serial-number="2032909350" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Icfe0c5b474d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Cumberland Contractors, Inc. v. State Bank and Trust Co., 327 Ga. App. 121, 755 S.E.2d 511 (2014)</cite.query><?page no="165"?>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 6:8<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
